Overview

  1. In these files, code is shown in light grey boxes
    • Mouse over the upper right corner of each box to see a clipboard icon
    • Click on the icon to copy the code and then paste it in your R
  2. In R, many specialized functions are in packages
    • You need to install a package in order to use it
      • You only need to do this once per device
      • For example, to install the haven package:
        • install.packages("haven")
        • Or use the Rstudio GUI: Packages pane
    • You need to load a package in order to use it
      • You load or âlibraryâ a package once per file or session
      • For example, to load the haven package:
        • library(haven)
  3. There are a number of thing about R that can cause you problems
    • R is case-sensitive
      • VARIABLE is not the same as variable
    • You can assign something to a name using <- (an arrow)
      • This is NOT the same as = (equal sign)
    • Students often get errors when trying to install packages in a script
      • Especially when itâs a package thatâs already installed
      • Itâs better to install them separately, either through the Rstudio packages pane or the console *These are the packages weâll use today, so you can install them:
        • haven
        • dplyr
        • ggplot2
        • broom

Data

Read in data

  • The haven package lets you read (and write) SPSS, SAS, and Stata files
    • Another option is the foreign package, but itâs older and doesnât work quite as well
  • This data file is saved as an SPSS file called data1.sav
  • Iâm reading in the file and putting it in a data frame object in R called data1
    • This will let us refer to it later by name
      • In general, itâs good to name everything: data, models, etc.
library(haven)
data1 <- read_sav("data1.sav")
  • There are two X variables and two Y variables
    • y2 is just a recoded version of y1
      • y2 is 1 if y1 \(\ge\) 0 and 0 if y1 \(\lt\) 0

View data

  • The head() function shows you the first 6 rows (by default) of a data frame
    • The n = 10 option shows the first 10 rows instead

Create new variables

  • Sometimes we want to create new variables based on existing ones, such as
    • Mean center variables
    • Create interaction terms
  • There are many ways to do this
    • If you have a way you like, use it
    • If you donât, I like the mutate() function in the dplyr package
      • dplyr is part of a group of packages called the tidyverse
library(dplyr)

Attaching package: 'dplyr'
The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':

    filter, lag
The following objects are masked from 'package:base':

    intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
data1 <- data1 %>%
    mutate(x1c = x1 - mean(x1),
           x2c = x2 - mean(x2),
           x1cx2c = x1c * x2c)
head(data1)
# A tibble: 6 Ã 7
     x1     x2       y1    y2    x1c    x2c x1cx2c
  <dbl>  <dbl>    <dbl> <dbl>  <dbl>  <dbl>  <dbl>
1 11.2   3.12   11.7        1  0.681  0.893  0.608
2 11.4  -3.78  -20.3        0  0.929 -6.01  -5.58 
3  9.78  4.11   22.6        1 -0.709  1.89  -1.34 
4  9.09 -4.62  -12.4        0 -1.40  -6.85   9.57 
5 11.2   2.71   20.9        1  0.721  0.479  0.346
6  6.36 -0.680   0.0911     1 -4.13  -2.91  12.0
  • data1 <- data1 means weâre adding the new variables to the existing data1 data frame
  • %>% symbol
    • Take the thing on the left side and do the stuff on the right side to it
    • Take data1 and create these new variables (in the mutate() function) in it
  • You can create several new variables with one mutate() statement
    • Separate them with commas
    • Here, I mean center x1, mean center x2, and create their product term

Plots

  • The best way to make plots is using the ggplot2 package (also part of the tidyverse)
  • You can make many exciting plots, but for now, weâre going to make some histograms and some scatterplots

Histograms

library(ggplot2)

ggplot(data = data1, aes(x = y1)) + 
    geom_histogram()
`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

ggplot(data = data1, aes(x = y2)) + 
    geom_histogram()
`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

  • The aes() function is where youâll tell ggplot2 about which variables will be in the plot

    • Here, y1 in the first plot and y2 in the second

  • geom_histogram() makes a histogram

  • You can change just about every aspect of the plot

    • Colors
    • Add legend
    • Change background

  • I like a little bit cleaner theme: theme_classic()

ggplot(data = data1, aes(x = y1)) + 
    geom_histogram() +
    theme_classic()
`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Scatterplots

  • A histogram uses only 1 variable, but a scatterplot needs 2
    • Supply both x and y in the aes() function
    • Iâm plotting x1 on the x axis
      • y1 on the y axis in the first plot
      • y2 on the y axis in the second plot
    • geom_point() plots the points (i.e., makes a scatterplot)
ggplot(data = data1, aes(x = x1, y = y1)) + 
    geom_point()

ggplot(data = data1, aes(x = x1, y = y2)) + 
    geom_point()

  • Weâll see this a lot with categorical variables
    • They often take on just a few possible values
    • The points are all on top of each other and hard to see
  • There are two good ways to deal with this easily
    • Reduce the alpha (opacity) of the points
      • Ranges from 0 (see-through) to 1 (opaque)
    • Change the point symbol to an outline-only symbol
      • All the possible options are here
    • Iâm also increasing the size of the symbols to make them easier to see
    • And changing the theme because the grey background makes it harder to see
ggplot(data = data1, aes(x = x1, y = y2)) + 
    geom_point(alpha = 0.2, size = 3) +
    theme_classic()

ggplot(data = data1, aes(x = x1, y = y2)) + 
    geom_point(shape = 1, size = 3) +
    theme_classic()

  • Iâm doing the wrong model here
    • I have x1, x2, and their interaction
    • Nothing is centered
    • Donât do this
bad_interaction <- lm(y1 ~ x1 + x2 + x1*x2, data1)
summary(bad_interaction)

Linear regression (with interaction)

  • Use mean centered predictors: x1c and x2c
  • Use the centered product too: x1cx2c
model1_lr <- lm(y1 ~ x1c + x2c + x1cx2c, data1)

GLiM. (with interaction)

  • This is the exact same model, just using the GLiM procedure
    • Remember that linear regression is a GLiM with normal residuals and identity link function
  • family = gaussian(link = "identity"))
    • family is about the random component (i.e., distribution of residuals)
    • link = identity is about the link function
model1_glim <- glm(y1 ~ x1c + x2c + x1cx2c, data1, 
                   family = gaussian(link = "identity"))
summary(model1_glim)

Call:
glm(formula = y1 ~ x1c + x2c + x1cx2c, family = gaussian(link = "identity"),

  • This is still just a linear regression, so most things look the same â in fact, most things are exactly numerically the same
    • Coefficients

      • Instead thereâs a deviance, which weâll use later

Residual plots

  • In order to make residuals plots, we need the residuals
    • There are several ways to do this
    • I like the broom package and its augment() function
      • It adds a bunch of things, including residuals, to the model output and saves it all as a data frame, so you can use it
      • It also works for most models you might run, including lm(), glm(), lme(), etc.
library(broom)
aug_m1lr <- augment(model1_lr)
head(aug_m1lr)

  • This data frame (aug_m1lr) includes the observations from the model (y1, x1c, x2c, x1cx2c) as well as
    • Predicted values (.fitted)
    • Raw residuals (.resid)
    • Other diagnostics
  • You can plots the residuals vs the predictors (x1c and x2c) or vs the predicted value (.fitted)
    • In both situations, if the model is working, you should see the same thing
      • No relationship (i.e., flat line)
      • Constant variance
  • Adding geom_smooth() (with no additional options) to your ggplot() creates a moving average or loess line with a confidence interval
    • Should look like a roughly flat line with equal confidence interval
      • Ignore minor deviations are left or right edges: Running average gets weird when you get to the ends
ggplot(data = aug_m1lr, aes(x = x1c, y = .resid)) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_smooth()
`geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

ggplot(data = aug_m1lr, aes(x = x2c, y = .resid)) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_smooth()
`geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

ggplot(data = aug_m1lr, aes(x = .fitted, y = .resid)) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_smooth()
`geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

  • All of these plots look pretty good
    • The line is pretty straight, pretty flat
    • The confidence interval is pretty even across the whole plot (except the ends, which will always flare a little like that)

    • Predictors: x1c, x2c, x1cx2c
    • How do the results differ from the model with y1 as the outcome?
  • Plot the residuals versus the predicted scores
    • Include the loess line with confidence interval
    • How do the residuals look? Good? Bad?
  • Plot a histogram of the residuals
    • This specific plot is not in this handout
    • Whatâs going on here? Does this look like you want it to?
